Hate Crimes Before and After the 2016 Election

Yuren Pang, Kaia Lund, Kayla Hostetler

5/3/2018

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(gridExtra)

In the fivethirtyeight \(\href{https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/higher-rates-of-hate-crimes-are-tied-to-income-inequality/}{\text{article}}\), Maimuna Majumber concluded that hate crimes are tied to income inequality by analyzing the correlations between hate crimes rate and nine different socioeconomic factors. We were motivated by exploring the statistical techniques to identify the social problems and make social impacts. In this Math 155 miniproject, we conducted a confirmatory research on Majumber’s conclusion, specifically how does the income inquality (measured by the Gini index) impact the average number of hate incidents (per 100,000 people)? In addition, we were very interested in the role of Donald Trump’s election in changing the hate crime incidents. Therefore, we pose another two research questions: how does the percent of population voted for Trump affect the average number of hate crimes in general? Or, do the two factors play any roles in influencing hate crimes at all?

Choosing Our Dataset

We based our project off of the fivethirtyeight data. The dataset contains nine potential socioeconomic factors which potentially impact the pre and post election hate crime rates in 51 states. The main variables that we used are: 1) Gini index which measures the income inequality in each state (gini_index), 2) the percent of population voted for Trump in each state (share_vote_trump), 3) the pre-election average number of hate crimes (per 100,000 people) in one year from 2010 to 2015 (avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi), 4) the post-election number of hate crimes ((per 100,000 people) in ten days after the 2016 election (hate_crimes_per_100k_splc).

library(fivethirtyeight)
data(hate_crimes)

Majumber’s Analysis

First of all, we would like to test Majumber’s conclusion. Before the testing, we started off by visualizing the two important response variables: the pre-election and post-election number of hate crimes. Note that the pre-election measures the average number in one year from 2010 to 2015, whereas the post-election measures the incidents which happened in ten days.

#The pre-election average number of hate crimes in a year
pre.his <- ggplot(hate_crimes, aes(x=avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi))+
  geom_histogram(fill = "red") +
  labs(x="Pre-Election Hate Crimes per 100k People (FBI)")

#The post-election number of hate crimes in ten days
post.his <- ggplot(hate_crimes, aes(x=hate_crimes_per_100k_splc))+
  geom_histogram(fill = "blue") +
  labs(x="Post-Election Hate Crimes per 100k People (SPLC)")

grid.arrange(pre.his, post.his, widths = c(1,1), nrow=1)

After gaining some insights, we followed Majumber’s analysis and explored the relationship between these data and the income inequality (Gini index).

#pre-election relationship between gini_index and hate crimes data from the fbi
pre.vis <- ggplot(hate_crimes, aes(x=gini_index, y=avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm") +
  geom_text(aes(label=state)) +
  labs(x="GINI Index", y="Average Hate Crimes per 100k People (FBI)")

#post-election relationship between gini_index and hate crimes data from the splc
post.vis <- ggplot(hate_crimes, aes(x=gini_index, y=hate_crimes_per_100k_splc)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm") +
  geom_text(aes(label=state)) +
  labs(x="GINI Index", y="Hate Crimes per 100k People (SPLC)")

grid.arrange(pre.vis, post.vis, nrow = 1)

What we found in the visualization is that there indeed is a very strong positive relationship between the number of hate crimes and the Gini index. Does this mean that Majumber is right in his conclusion?

Removing the Outliers

What stood out was the fact that there is one outlier with extremely high numbers of hate crimes in all four visualizations. It turned out that the outlier is District of Columbia. Then, we removed the outlier. Note that the FBI data do not have information in Hawaii whereas the SPLC data do not have numbers in Hawaii, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Wyoming. That’s why we created two new dataset.

#Outlier removed of the pre-election hate crimes variable
hate_crimes1 <- hate_crimes %>% 
  filter(avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi < 9)

#Outlier removed in the post-election hate crimes variable
hate_crimes2 <- hate_crimes %>%
  filter(hate_crimes_per_100k_splc < 1.5)

Then, we constructed new multivariate linear regressions and explored the relationships between the same variables in Majumber’s analysis.

#Pre-election
rem.out.pre <- ggplot(hate_crimes1, aes(x=gini_index, y=avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm") + geom_text(aes(label=state)) +
  labs(x="GINI Index", y="Hate Crimes per 100k People (FBI) - Outlier Removed")

#Post-election
rem.out.post <- ggplot(hate_crimes2, aes(x=gini_index, y=hate_crimes_per_100k_splc)) +

grid.arrange(rem.out.pre, rem.out.post, nrow = 1)

#The big p-value indicates a weak significance.
model_fbi <- lm(avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi ~ gini_index, hate_crimes1)
summary(model_fbi)

The pre-election data (FBI, hate crimes per 100k people) only has a slight positive relationship with the gini index and there is a slight negative relationship between the post election data (SPLC, hate crimes per 100k people) and the gini index. As a matter of fact, two models with \(p_1 = 0.702\) and \(p_2 = 0.453\) indicate that we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the coefficient \(b=0\) if we would like to be 95% confident. (The alternative hypothesis would be \(b \neq 0\).) As a result, we found significant flaws of the analysis in the fivethirtyeight article by removing the outlier of District of Columbia. It was because of the outlier of the District of Columbia that Majumber found a strong positive relationship between hate crimes rate and the Gini index.

Create a New Variable: crime_diff

To further test that our rejection of the Fivethirtyeight article, we create a new variable: crime_diff which measures the change of daily number of hate crimes in each state after the 2016 election. Note that due to the lack of data in the post-election hate crimes variable, we can only use 46 states without District of Columbia (the outlier), Hawaii, North Dakota, South Dakota, and Wyoming.

#Create a new variable to measure the daily hate crime number change before and after the election except five states
hate_crimes_new <- hate_crimes2 %>% 
  mutate(crime_diff = hate_crimes_per_100k_splc/10 - avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi/365)

ggplot(hate_crimes_new, aes(x=gini_index, y=crime_diff)) + 
  geom_point()+
  geom_text(aes(label=state))+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")+
  labs(x="GINI Index", y="Crime Difference")

#This model indicates that there is no relationship between the change of hate crimes and income inequality.
model_diff <- lm(crime_diff ~ gini_index, hate_crimes_new)
summary(model_diff)
##

## lm(formula = crime_diff ~ gini_index, data = hate_crimes_new)

Still, 0 would fall in the 95% confidence interval in this model. The measure of hate crime changes after election did not support the fivethirtyeight’s conclusion, either. Therefore, we can reject the conclusion on the Fivethirtyeight article after the outlier is removed based on the dataset we have.

Trump and Hate Crimes?

It is \(\href{https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-nation/wp/2018/03/23/hate-crimes-rose-the-day-after-trump-was-elected-fbi-data-show/?noredirect=on&utm_term=.ddfa67f4c565}{\text{reported}}\) that hate crimes rose the days after Trump was elected. We were very interested the role of Trump’s election in 2016 in the hate crimes dynamics and would like to explore the role with the aid of the data in the hate_crimes_new based on the given dataset hate_crimes. Because the SPLC did not have data in North Dakota, South Dakota, Wyoming, we decided to use the daily crime change after the election crime_diff as the response variable. We explored the following relationship between the share of people voted for Trump and the increase (or decrease) of hate crimes in each state.

ggplot(hate_crimes_new, aes(x=share_vote_trump, y=crime_diff, col = avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi)) + 
  geom_point()+
  geom_text(aes(label=state))+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")+
  labs(x="Share Voted for Trump", y="Crime Difference", col = "pre-election hate crimes")

#this model indicates that there is a strong significance between the share_vote_trump and the increase of hate crimes in a state
model_diff <- lm(crime_diff ~ share_vote_trump + avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi, hate_crimes_new)
summary(model_diff)

Intuitively we would think that the more people voted for Trump, the number of hate crimes would increase more. However, the above model illustrates that there is strong negative relationship between the two variables. It indicates that the redder states tend to have less increase in the hate crimes. This is rather surprising. Although we found this significant relationship, we could not ascertain the reason behind this discovery. Initially, we thought it could result from the fact that the redder states had higher numbers of hate crimes before the election so there could not have been much room for increase. Therefore, We assigned different colors to each state based on the hate crime numbers before (darker color means lower number of hate crimes). However, we found that most redder states on the bottom right corner such as Oklahoma and Alabama had lower average hate crimes compared with blue states such as Massachusetts, Washington, and Oregon which had very high post-election increase of hate crimes.

The above model also indicates that the 95% confidence interval is \(-0.112374 \leq \text{share_vote_trump} \leq -0.012974\) (the standard error is 0.024850). However, the p-value of the avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi is 0.08798 (since our null hypothesis would be \(c_0 = 0\) whereas the alternative hypothesis would be \(c_0 \neq 0\)). Therefore, we can be 95% confident that there is a negative relationship between the hate crime changes and the share of population who voted for Trump. However, if we maintain the 95% confidence level, we can draw any conclusion between the pre-election hate crime and hate crime changes.

Hence, we need research on this finding with more comprehensive dataset in the future.

Make a Prediction of the Hate Crime Changes

In the end, we would like to show the practicality of our project. We would like to predict the potential changes of hate crimes given the pre-election hate crimes data. We conduct a model in which the pre-election hate crimes is the predictor and the change of hate crimes is the response variable. We created our null hypothesis that there is no correlation between pre-election hate crimes and the post-election change of hate crimes \(c = 0\). Our alternative hypothesis is that the higher the number of hate crimes each state has, the more hate crimes they would encounter after the election. \(c > 0\)

ggplot(hate_crimes_new, aes(x=avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi, y=crime_diff, col=share_vote_trump)) + 
  geom_point()+
  geom_text(aes(label=state))+
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

model_predictor <- lm(crime_diff ~ avg_hatecrimes_per_100k_fbi, hate_crimes_new)
summary(model_predictor)

We are more than 95% confident that there is a positive relationship between hate crime changes and the average numbers of hate crimes before election.

The Conclusion and Concerns

In this report, we found that the there is no significant relationship between hate crimes and income inequality after we analyzed the dataset without the outlier of Washington DC. We also found that there is a significant negative relationship between the hate crime changes and the share of people who voted for Trump. We also made the inference in the end that the more hate crimes you have, the even more increase hate crimes the state will encounter.

However, we can only reasonably draw these conclusion based on the given hate_crimes dataset. The response variable we used pose some limitations for our research. The FBI data set covered years 2011-2015 and the SPLC data covered the 10 days following the election. The FBI only collects prosecutable hate crime data from law enforcement agencies (which excludes white nationalist speeches on college campuses, etc.), whereas the Southern Poverty Law Center counts non-prosecutable hate crimes as well. Besides the different measurements, the pre-election data are mostly voluntarily submitted by victims whereas the post-election data came from a variety of media accounts and self-reported form entries. In addition, this only collects the data of one election circle. To make stronger inference on what would influence the hate crime changes, it would be very helpful to gain data over the course of several elections. In general, hate crimes statistics are very difficult to collect. It is possible that our findings are not entirely correct. More comprehensive research needs to be conducted in the future to test our findings.
